@chapter The input language syntax

The @code{radtest} program gets as its argument the filename of the test
script to run. Currently its syntax is very simple: It consists of
the statements of three kinds:

@enumerate 1
@item Assignment statements
@item Send statements
@item Expect statements
@end enumerate

Each statement is terminated by a semicolon. The statements are
discussed in detail below.

@subheading Expressions

The term @dfn{expression} in the discussion below means one of the
following:

@table @asis
@item 1. Dereferenced variable name.
This is the name of a previously defined variable with a @samp{$}
sign prepended to it, e.g: @code{$VAR}. In this case the resulting
value is that of the variable being dereferenced.	

@item 2. String enclosed in double quotes
E.g. @code{"a string"}

@item 3. Integer value

@item 4. IP address
IP addresses are specified in `dotted quad' notation,
e.g. @code{127.0.0.1}

@item 5. An A/V pair list.
A comma-separated list of A/V pairs. The whole list is enclosed
in curly braces. Each pair is represented by the following construct:

@example
		@var{dict_name} = @var{value}
@end example

@noindent
where @var{dict_name} is a valid radius dictionary name, i.e.
the name which is listed in @code{ATTRIBUTE} statement in one
of the radius dictionary files.

For example the following is a valid value-pair list:

@example
@{ NAS-Name = "localhost", NAS-IP-Address = 127.0.0.1,
   NAS-Port-Id = 1, User-Name = $name @}
@end example

@item 6. Concatenation
This means a concatenation of the two or more value-pair lists. The
sign for such concatenation is @samp{+}. For example, assuming

@example
a = @{ NAS-Name = "localhost,
       NAS-IP-Address = 127.0.0.1 @};
b = @{ NAS-Port-Id = 1, User-Name = $name @};
@end example

@noindent
the statement:

@example
		$a + $b
@end example
@noindent
would produce the same list as in the example above, except
that the @code{$name} will be already substituted by its value.

@item 7. Dictionary name
This means a valid radius dictionary value name, i.e. the name which
is listed in a @code{VALUE} statement in one of the radius
dictionary files.

@end table
	

@subheading An assignment statement

This statement assigns a value to a variable. Syntax is:

@example
@var{variable_name} = @var{expression} ;
@end example

@noindent
where @var{variable_name} is a name of a variable, @var{value} is its
value. The @samp{=} and @samp{;} are required. 

@subheading Send statement

This statement sends the packet to the radius server.

The syntax is:

@example
send auth @var{PACKET_CODE} @var{PAIRLIST}
send acct @var{PACKET_CODE} @var{PAIRLIST}
@end example

@noindent
where @var{PACKET_CODE} is the integer value of the radius packet code,
@var{PAIRLIST} is a value-pair list to be sent to the server.

The following statement:

@example
send auth 1 @{ User-Name = "hamlet", Password = "pwd",
               NAS-IP-Address = 127.0.0.1, NAS-Port-Id = 1 @} ;
@end example

@noindent
sends the radius authentication request (code 1) to authenticate the
user @samp{hamlet} with password @samp{pwd} coming from the port 1 on
the NAS 127.0.0.1.

The statement:

@example
send acct 4 @{ Acct-Status-Type = Start,
               Acct-Session-Id = "00" @} +
            @{ User-Name = "hamlet", Password = "pwd",
               NAS-IP-Address = 127.0.0.1, NAS-Port-Id = 1 @} ;
@end example
@noindent
sends the accounting record (code 4) for the above user, querying
server to mark the start of his session.

@subheading Expect statement

The expect statement follows the syntax:

@example
expect @var{CODE} ;
expect @var{CODE} @var{FAILURE_MESSAGE} ;
@end example

@noindent
where @var{CODE} is an integer number of the response packet to expect
from the radius server. If the server replies with this code, the
statement succeeds, otherwise it fails, prints the diagnostics on
stderr and @code{radtest} finishes its execution.

The @var{FAILURE_MESSAGE} is a string to display when the expect fails
instead of the standard message;

@comment *L2****************************************************************
@node radtest examples,              , radtest syntax, Radtest
@chapter Examples of @code{radtest} scripts

@subheading Authentication test

The following script sends the authentication request to the server

@example

auth_packet = @{ User-Name = $username, Password = $password,
		 NAS-Port-Id = $port,
		 NAS-Identifier = "localhost",
		 NAS-IP-Address = 127.0.0.1 @};

send auth 1 $auth_packet;
expect 2 "Returned " $REPLY_CODE ", Reply-Message = " $REPLY[Reply-Message] ;

## EOF
@end example

Before calling this script, the variables @code{username},
@code{password} and @code{port} must be assigned corresponding values.
If the above script is saved in the file @file{auth.t}, then it can
be run as:

@example
% radtest username=\"gray\" password=\"foo\" port=1 auth.t
@end example
@noindent
Note the use of quotes to assign string values and the use of escape
characters (@samp{\}) to prevent the quotes from being interpreted by
the shell.

@subheading Accounting test

@example

send acct 4 @{ User-Name = $username,
		Acct-Status-Type = $type,
		Acct-Session-Id = $sid,
		NAS-Port-Id = $port,
		NAS-Identifier = "localhost",
		NAS-IP-Address = 127.0.0.1 @};
expect 5;
@end example

This script can be run as:

@example
% radtest username=\"gray\" sid=\"abc\" port=1 type=Start acct.t
@end example
@noindent

to send a start request or as:

@example
